{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486928"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"209"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/209"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.13,0.39,0.32,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92232"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/209"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75556"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"926"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31298"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92232"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal pain. He had been playing football earlier in the day and was kicked in the left upper abdomen. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 98% on room air. He has tenderness in the left upper quadrant. No abnormality was detected by the bedside abdominal ultrasound. A CT scan is performed which shows a 4 cm laceration across the lower pole of the spleen with a blush adjacent to the splenic hilum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopy and splenectomy","Laparotomy and splenorrhaphy","Angiography and embolisation","Continued observation","Laparotomy and splenectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a Grade III splenic injury - as defined with a laceration \u0026gt;3 cm. The observation of a \u0027blush\u0027 during the arterial phase of the CT scan implies active bleeding, with extravasation and pooling of contrast. This finding of ongoing bleeding in a haemodynamically stable patient is an indication for angiographic intervention\u003Cstrong\u003E (angiography and embolisation)\u003C/strong\u003E. Should embolisation fail or the patient become unstable, surgery (e.g.\u003Cstrong\u003E  laparotomy +/- splenectomy)\u003C/strong\u003E may then be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe guidelines for the management of blunt or penetrating splenic trauma are made according to the degree of injury to the organ (based on the American Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST)) and the haemodynamic status of the patient. Whilst an initial conservative should be considered for all patients, if there is evidence of haemodynamic instability, then the need for operative intervention must be weighed up. The table shows guidelines - but these are not absolute and each case must be judged on its own merits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A patient with suspected splenic injury should undergo prompt CT evaluation if haemodynamically stable"],"references":["Scarborough JE, Ingraham AM, Liepert AE, Jung HS, O\u0027Rourke AP, Agarwal SK. Nonoperative Management Is as Effective as Immediate Splenectomy for Adult Patients with High-Grade Blunt Splenic Injury. J Am Coll Surg. 2016;223(2):249-58. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27112125/","Coccolini F, Montori G, Catena F, et al. Splenic trauma: WSES classification and guidelines for adult and pediatric patients. World J Emerg Surg. 2017. 12. Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-017-0151-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75556"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"209"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14447"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14447"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1e9f0f09-6d9f-42b7-9f95-e2d29b2b3445.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1e9f0f09-6d9f-42b7-9f95-e2d29b2b3445.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":942,"height":396}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75556"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T21:55:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T21:56:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"209"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92232"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":